<div id="review_2966156035" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2966156035" />
    <a title="Clare Grové" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33886901-clare-grov"><img alt="Clare Grové" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1555836627p2/33886901.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2966156035?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clare Grové" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clare Grové" href="/user/show/33886901-clare-grov">Clare Grové</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33886901-clare-grov?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33886901-clare-grov?shelf=audiobooks-2019">audiobooks-2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2966156035" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18390822784759688921">&quot;Audible hopes that you have enjoyed this programme&quot;. <br/>&apos;Enjoy&apos; is certainly not my experience of this autobiography. How can one &apos;enjoy&apos; hearing about atrocities and abuses committed against your fellow human beings in the land of your birth? A more fitting line for me would be &quot;Audible hopes that you were <i>moved</i> by this programme&quot;. <br/><br/>I have learned more about the daily <s>life</s> existence of black people in South Africa in the 18½ hours of this audiobook than I have in my 42 year life span living in the</span>
  <span id="freeText18390822784759688921" style="display:none">"Audible hopes that you have enjoyed this programme". <br />'Enjoy' is certainly not my experience of this autobiography. How can one 'enjoy' hearing about atrocities and abuses committed against your fellow human beings in the land of your birth? A more fitting line for me would be "Audible hopes that you were <i>moved</i> by this programme". <br /><br />I have learned more about the daily <s>life</s> existence of black people in South Africa in the 18½ hours of this audiobook than I have in my 42 year life span living in the said country.<br /><br />The post 1994 history books speak of the 'suffering' of black people, the 1956 march on the capital, the Sharpeville massacre in 1960, the student uprising in '76, the arrest, trial, imprisonment and release of Mandela. <br />But the word 'suffering' is 'euphemistic' and a glossing over of actual happenings, because nowhere have I read (and I have studied, and taught Social Science in South African schools post '94) about the hand to mouth existence, the school brutalities and the difficulties in obtaining and maintaining a pass book (aptly named the 'dompas' (dumb / stupid pass)). <br />To get a job, get a pass. To get a pass, you need a job. To have attained said job, you would have broken the law by being in an area which bars you legally. An entire system designed to see people fail. An entire system designed to quell the human spirit of survival and triumph and progress. An entire system that goes against all I believe in. But a system of which I was, and still am, a beneficiary.<br /><br />I am crying as I type this. I am crying for the injustice. I am crying for the hatred caused. I am crying. <br /><br />God bless Africa<br />Lord Bless Africa<br />May her glory be lifted high<br />Hear our petitions<br />Lord bless us. Us your children<br />Lord we ask You to protect our nation<br />Intervene and end all conflicts<br />Protect us, protect us<br />Protect our nation<br />Protect South Africa<br />[<i>Nkosi Sikelel iafrika</i> ~ Enoch Sontonga]<br /><br />We <i>need</i> books such as this (I cannot bring myself to type the title of the book because it is a word that I hate and a word that carries hatred) to be mandatory reading in South African schools. We <i>need</i> more books that speak of the daily horrors of apartheid - perhaps some that do not have the 'happy ending' of this book with Johannes aka Mark aka Thanyani ('the wise one') escaping South Africa and succeeding through sport and education. We <i>need</i> books that show the continued hardships and suffering (there we go with that word again) of generations of black South Africans.<br />We <i>need</i> understanding. We <i>need</i> empathy. We <i>need</i> change.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18390822784759688921" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


