<div id="review_3597471692" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3597471692" />
    <a title="Hunter Quinn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25920232-hunter-quinn"><img alt="Hunter Quinn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589898902p2/25920232.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3597471692?book_show_action=true">Nov 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hunter Quinn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hunter Quinn" href="/user/show/25920232-hunter-quinn">Hunter Quinn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Americans; those interested in South African history</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3597471692" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13460348725110565530">Mark Mathabane grew up as a black boy in 1960s/70s South Africa. His story is one of brutality, grace, and survival. By the end, I found myself agreeing with his statement: &quot;Apartheid is a holocaust without the gas chambers.&quot;<br/><br/>This book is not for the faint of heart. He describes the unthinkable in vivid detail: stories of nightly police raids, starvation, disease, murder, prostitution, rape. Mathabane did not tell me about apartheid. He made me *feel* apartheid. In just a small way, I began to sh</span>
  <span id="freeText13460348725110565530" style="display:none">Mark Mathabane grew up as a black boy in 1960s/70s South Africa. His story is one of brutality, grace, and survival. By the end, I found myself agreeing with his statement: "Apartheid is a holocaust without the gas chambers."<br /><br />This book is not for the faint of heart. He describes the unthinkable in vivid detail: stories of nightly police raids, starvation, disease, murder, prostitution, rape. Mathabane did not tell me about apartheid. He made me *feel* apartheid. In just a small way, I began to share Mathabane's turbulent emotional life. Whenever white people appeared in this book, I felt myself recoil slightly in fear and anger. I too racked my brains to come up with solutions to Mathabane's woes. At times, I had to put this book down and take a break from scenes of evil. <br /><br />It is a miracle that Mathabane was not consumed by rage. Not only did he survive, he became a caring and sympathetic individual. However, Mathabane makes it clear that the exception proves the rule: apartheid killed physically and emotionally. Those who survived childhood lived as mere shadows of their former selves. <br /><br />Why did Mathabane turn out differently? The author gives three answers. (1) Mathabane himself was both smart and gifted. He faced all his difficulties with superhuman effort. (2) His mother and grandmother sacrificed everything for him. These amazing women act as the constant thread in his life. Mathabane succeeded because these two women picked up their crosses and figuratively died for him. (3) The three white people whom Mathabane befriended sacrificed their own power. While they gave him money at times, their sacrifices occurred in other, more important ways. They tapped into their social networks to assist Mathabane. They risked their reputations, and sometimes even their lives to help him. This changed everything. In the apartheid system, reasons 1 and 2 would have come to nothing without reason 3. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13460348725110565530" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

