    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1034467028" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1034467028" />
    <a title="Mindy McAdams" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5456705-mindy-mcadams"><img alt="Mindy McAdams" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509202987p2/5456705.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1034467028?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mindy McAdams" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mindy McAdams" href="/user/show/5456705-mindy-mcadams">Mindy McAdams</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11413013-kaffir-boy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5456705-mindy-mcadams?shelf=africa">africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5456705-mindy-mcadams?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1034467028" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5286460718376785926">The first half (or maybe two-thirds) was much more interesting than the last part of the book, where the author seems to be dragging things out as he waits and hopes to get a scholarship to a U.S. university. As tennis became more prominent in the book -- as part of the author&apos;s plan to escape apartheid South Africa -- my interest waned.<br/><br/>That said, I was very interested in the story from the beginning up until after the account of the Soweto riots of 1976, when black schoolchildren were massacred</span>
  <span id="freeText5286460718376785926" style="display:none">The first half (or maybe two-thirds) was much more interesting than the last part of the book, where the author seems to be dragging things out as he waits and hopes to get a scholarship to a U.S. university. As tennis became more prominent in the book -- as part of the author's plan to escape apartheid South Africa -- my interest waned.<br /><br />That said, I was very interested in the story from the beginning up until after the account of the Soweto riots of 1976, when black schoolchildren were massacred in the streets by police. The story begins when Mark (then called Johannes) was small, maybe four years old. He's the oldest of three children at that point; eventually there are seven children in his family. From the beginning, there's never enough to eat. Both his parents work, but their pay is so little it barely covers the rent. Their rented shack is tiny, and the children sleep on cardboard on the floor.<br /><br />Some of the things I realized while reading this: black people in South Africa at that time had to pay fees for every little thing, such as leaving the township to look for work, or to get a permit to allow them to go to a job. I had heard about the passbooks every black adult had to carry, but I didn't realize the extent to which the passbook -- filled with stamps and permits -- was used deliberately to make their lives more miserable. Numerous rules and regulations acted as brick walls to prevent people from getting an education, health care, and other basics. As a first-person account of that experience, this book is powerful. When the author's father got laid off from his job, he was thrown in jail for not having a job! <br /><br />Johannes's mother and grandmother stand out as strong characters in the story, and without their commitment and tenacity, it's clear Johannes would never have gone to school at all, let alone stayed in until he graduated from high school. <br /><br />Today in South Africa, a large number of black children still have terrible schools, oppressive fees, no books or poor books, and far fewer resources than the children of more privileged families. Yet some changes have come about -- Johannes was almost prohibited from the only school open to him because his mother and father came from two different language groups, and the school would only admit children whose mother tongue was a particular one. Had he answered questions about his mother tongue differently, the school might have excluded him altogether.<br /><br />I remember reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/92057.The_Autobiography_of_Malcolm_X" title="The Autobiography of Malcolm X by Malcolm X" rel="nofollow noopener">The Autobiography of Malcolm X</a> in high school; it opened my eyes to many things in my own country I knew nothing about. This book is similarly mind-opening and surprising, even though I have visited South Africa twice and read other accounts about its history. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5286460718376785926" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

