<div id="review_1070978692" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1070978692" />
    <a title="Stephen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4250414-stephen"><img alt="Stephen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1295290277p2/4250414.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1070978692?book_show_action=true">Oct 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen" href="/user/show/4250414-stephen">Stephen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1070978692" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5537154369975340035"> What was it like to grow up in South Africa in the Apartheid of the sixties? Mark Mathabane survived and was able to get to America, get educated , and become a productive member of society. Millions of others never made it. And even to this day, many blacks still are unable to break the remaining bonds of Apartheid.....even in modern South Africa.<br/> There are many books where one will say they really enjoyed reading it but I can&apos;t use the word &apos;enjoyed&apos; when reviewing this book and yet....This w</span>
  <span id="freeText5537154369975340035" style="display:none"> What was it like to grow up in South Africa in the Apartheid of the sixties? Mark Mathabane survived and was able to get to America, get educated , and become a productive member of society. Millions of others never made it. And even to this day, many blacks still are unable to break the remaining bonds of Apartheid.....even in modern South Africa.<br /> There are many books where one will say they really enjoyed reading it but I can't use the word 'enjoyed' when reviewing this book and yet....This was one of the best books I have ever read ! You follow the boy, Johanes, later just Mark as he grows from a child of 4 or 5 until he reaches young adulthood and is finally able to escape the bonds of Apartheid.You will meet his father who tries keep his tribal ways and you will meet Mark's loving mother who was always encouraging him to rise above his station. As much of a history buff that I might consider myself, never have I felt , really felt what it was like to grow up in the South Africa of the sixties and seventies! You will feel what it was like to live like Mark did but his courage will overwhelm you. <br /> And He lived to tell his tale so articulately that the images he paints will forever remain in your memory bank. Please read this marvelous book </span>
  <a data-text-id="5537154369975340035" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


